<HEADLINE>
<P>
PARK PLACES AGOURA IN LEAGUE LEAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL LAZARUS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Agoura High backup guard Mike Park took only two shots Wednesday night against 
Westlake. 
</P>
<P>
 Both were three-pointers that gave the Chargers leads, the second coming with 
one second to play and giving Agoura a 41-39 Marmonte league victory. 
</P>
<P>
 The victory left the Chargers (13-5, 7-1 in league play) alone in first place. 
</P>
<P>
 Park's three-pointer from the left baseline came after Westlake guard Steve 
Aylsworth (14 points) scored on a twisting lay-up to give the Warriors (10-5, 
4-3) the lead with 12 seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
 "This was the biggest shot of my career," Park said. "Coach said anyone who 
was open could take the shot. I was a little surprised I was open." 
</P>
<P>
 Forward Damon Blechen helped Agoura rally from an eight-point deficit midway 
through the third quarter by scoring nine of his 11 points in the final 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think we just played tougher defense in the fourth quarter," Blechen said. 
"It wasn't too much of a lead to overcome." 
</P>
<P>
 Westlake surged to an early 9-2 lead, helped by consecutive three-pointers by 
Aylsworth, who was making a rare start. Agoura came back in the second quarter, 
and Park's first three-pointer gave Agoura a 12-10 lead. 
</P>
<P>
 After going six minutes without scoring, Billy Miller (13 points), playing on 
a sprained ankle, scored seven points to help give Westlake a 19-17 halftime 
lead. 
</P>
<P>
 Agoura center Ben Richardson collided with Miller under the basket late in the 
third quarter and had to leave the game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
