<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: 2 HAZARDOUS WASTE CENTERS ARE OPEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SARA CATANIA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Emergency hazardous waste centers have opened in Simi Valley and Fillmore to 
collect leaky cans of paint thinner, broken bottles of pesticide and other 
toxic substances that were damaged in the Jan. 17 quake. 
</P>
<P>
 The collection centers, approved Tuesday by the Ventura County Board of 
Supervisors and coordinated by the county's General Services Agency and Waste 
Management Department, will be open through Sunday from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 The waste collection centers will accept motor oil, paint solvents, auto 
batteries, household cleaners, pesticides, fertilizers, antifreeze and other 
toxic refuse. 
</P>
<P>
 Individuals are limited to five gallons or 50 pounds of material per trip, and 
up to 20 gallons of used motor oil per trip. 
</P>
<P>
 In Fillmore, residents can turn in their waste at the Central Park parking lot 
at Central Avenue and Main Street. 
</P>
<P>
 Simi Valley residents can take hazardous waste to the Simi Valley Library, 
2969 Tapo Canyon Road. 
</P>
<P>
 For information, call the county Solid Waste Department at 529-2060, Ext. 
2060. SARA CATANIA 
</P>
</TEXT>
