<HEADLINE>
<P>
ASSEMBLYWOMAN MOORE TO RUN FOR SECRETARY OF STATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Assemblywoman Gwen Moore (D-Los Angeles) announced Wednesday that she will run 
for secretary of state next year to replace March Fong Eu, who has been 
nominated as President Clinton's ambassador to Micronesia. 
</P>
<P>
 First elected to the Assembly in 1978, Moore is chairwoman of the Utilities 
and Commerce Committee. 
</P>
<P>
 She is the third Democrat to enter the race. Los Angeles City Councilman Mike 
Woo and Eu's top deputy, Tony Miller, have announced their candidacies. 
</P>
<P>
 On the Republican side, former Assembly GOP leader Bill Jones of Fresno is 
running for the office. 
</P>
<P>
 Miller said Tuesday that Moore, 53, had failed to file required preliminary 
candidacy documents with the secretary of state's office and asked the Fair 
Political Practices Commission to investigate. Moore called the charge 
ridiculous and groundless and said she had filed the necessary papers. 
</P>
<P>
 Moore is the author of a 1992 family leave law that allows employees of 
businesses with 50 or more workers to take up to four months unpaid leave to 
care for newborn or sick children or sick parents or spouses without fear of 
losing their jobs. 
</P>
