<HEADLINE>
<P>
PERSONAL HEALTH; AH, THAT FIRST PUFF OF THE DAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KATHLEEN DOHENY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Never mind those old movies where no one can resist that after-sex smoke. 
Among hard-core puffers, the hands-down favorites are the after-dinner 
cigarette or the first one of the day, according to a new survey. 
</P>
<P>
 UCLA researcher Dr. Murray Jarvik and his colleagues interviewed more than 
5,000 Bay Area smokers, asking which cigarette of the day they would most miss. 
Forty-four percent said the after-dinner cigarette; 33% said the first puff of 
the day. 
</P>
<P>
 The after-romance cigarette? It ranked No. 15 behind the last cigarette of the 
day, the cigarette with coffee or alcohol, and those puffed during commute time 
or phone conversations. 
</P>
<P>
 Some respondents quit smoking for 24 hours and kept track of their withdrawal 
symptoms. The more nicotine-dependent, the more likely a smoker was to rate the 
first cigarette of the day as most important. 
</P>
<P>
 Smokers trying to quit or cut down might not realize how important certain 
cigarettes have become, says Jarvik, whose study was published in the Journal 
of Behavioral Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
 "Be prepared," he advises. "Have a coping mechanism ready." One option: "Get 
some nicotine chewing gum. It's difficult to smoke while chewing it." KATHLEEN 
DOHENY 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA012794-0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 007742 </DOCID>
